  "interpretation": {
    "architecture_boundary": "The replicated empirical failure occurs inside two ordinary end-to-end Transformer ranking families, but the experiment does not distinguish an architectural limit from supervision, data, or optimization causes.",
    "common_mode_boundary": "Common-mode response energy changes across objectives and families; it is not the defining mechanism.",
    "performance_consequence": "On strict-nonrepeat, history fails to deliver stable improvement over null, wrong-user history, random attribution of the same delta budget, or an independently trained QC model. The large label-aligned diagnostic gap is missed ranking opportunity, not a deployable or proven-learnable gain.",
    "positive_control": "All three supervised controls reliably convert history into direction and utility on exact-repeat requests, so strict-nonrepeat failure cannot be explained by inability to read history or optimize any history-dependent behavior.",
    "primary_motivation": "Ordinary LLM4Rec Transformers can react to user history and exploit recurrence, yet remain unreliable at assigning nonrepeat history response to the query-conditioned candidate direction that improves ranking."
  },
